AWU_COMMENTS: The recycled water supply comes from the San Jose/Santa Clara Regional Wastewater Facility, and is distributed by the South Bay Water Recycling Program to CII customers and multi family residential HOAs; recycled water is not used by single family residential customers.

The current classification of single family and multi family residential services, used in the eAR, likely undercounts multi family residential customers and needs to be reviewed for accuracy. We will be reviewing these residential classifications as we complete the CII classification.

* For FY24, the 90th percentile use threshold for SFR was 170 HCF. The 90th percentile use for MFR was 277 HCF.  Note for MFR this is water usage by water service account. There is a large range of dwelling units per account, so reporting water use by service account generally reflects our largest MFR buildings and doesn’t necessarily show the largest individual water use per dwelling unit in each MFR building. * The City of Santa Barbara engaged a consultant to perform an LAM Data Assessment in 2021. The assessment found that a total of 260 residential parcels had been excluded from the LAM data. The total irrigable irrigated area for those 260 residential parcels is 2,715,744.61 sf. The outdoor water use was calculated using the outdoor residential objective standard calculation =  0.8 x 2,715,744.61x 36.38 x 0.62. * Compared the LAM parcel numbers to City of Santa Barbara DIM meter parcel numbers. There are 338 residential parcels that have a DIM attached.There are 42 CII DIMs that were included in the LAM data. The total water use for those DIMs is reported here (cells B38 and B40).

SCV Water is currently developing its Water Use Efficiency Strategic Plan (WUESP) which will inlude in depth data analysis including, but not limited to, percentile use analysis by customer class. This information in not readily available at the time of the report submittal. Additonally, SCV Water is conducting its Cost of Service Study and will have this information available in Q3/Q4 of FY 25.

Regarding "landscapes misclassified or not captured in initial LAM analysis or not considered residential by supplier" (rows 35 40), SMWD has worked with a third party vendor to perform extensive landscape area measurements related to implementing SMWD's budget based rate structure for all its parcels and CII DIMS. Therefore, SMWD's data shows that the State's residential landscape area measurements incorrectly categorize a significant amount of CII DIM landscape area. Similarly, some parcels with DIMs were classified by the State as residential landscapes when they are actually CII landscapes. For these reasons, SMWD entered "YES" in rows 37 and 39. SMWD also provided, in row 38, a volume of DIM deliveries to residential landscapes. SMWD will wait to report volumes in Row 40  until SMWD is able to report CII DIM deliveries and CII DIM LAM in subsequent reporting periods as alternative supplier data.   In future reports, SMWD intends to submit alternative landscape area data for both Residential and CII DIM parcels, which will help SMWD more accurately calculate the volume of water used in each sector. These calculated water volumes may differ from what is recorded in the SAFER and eAR reports since this Conservation Framework defines water user categories and sums up consumption differently than SAFER or the eAR.   Moving forward, SMWD proposes working on a method that enables retailers to correct water use volumes they know are delivered to specific customer and landscape types.
For questions 35, 37, and 39, the City does not have the resources to evaluate the accuracy and or inaccuracy of the LAM data and therefore cannot confirm if the LAM data is accurate.
